{{Culture of the United States}}
The literature of [[Virginia]], [[United States]], includes fiction, poetry, and  nonfiction. Representative authors include [[Rita Dove]], [[Ellen Glasgow]], [[William Hoffman (author)|William Hoffman]], [[Lee Smith (fiction author)|Lee Smith]], [[Carolyn Kreiter-Foronda]] and [[William Styron]].{{sfn|Longest|2001}}{{sfn|Huggins|2003}} Journals featuring work of Virginia writers include the ''New Virginia Review'' (est. 1978), ''Richmond Quarterly'' (est. 1980), ''Edgar Allan Poe Review'' (est. 2000), and ''Virginia Adversaria'' (est. 2000).{{sfn|Huggins|2003}}

==History==
{{Expand section|date=March 2017 }}
A [[Global_spread_of_the_printing_press#North_America|printing press]] began operating in [[Jamestown, Virginia]], in 1682.<ref name=wroth1938>{{Citation |publisher = Southworth-Anthoensen Press |publication-place = Portland, Maine |title = The Colonial Printer |chapterurl = https://archive.org/stream/colonialprinter00wrot#page/15/mode/1up |via=Internet Archive |author = [[Lawrence C. Wroth]] |publication-date = 1938 |chapter=Diffusion of Printing }} (Fulltext)</ref> Colonial- and Federal-era writers included [[John Smith (explorer)|John Smith]] (''True Relation of Occurrences and Accidents in Virginia'', 1608); [[Robert Beverley, Jr.]] (''History and Present State of Virginia,'' 1705); Arthur Blackamore (''Religious Triumverate,'' 1720); [[Thomas Jefferson]] (''Notes on the State of Virginia,'' 1785).<ref name=Wilson1989begin>{{cite book |editor1= Charles Reagan Wilson |editor2= William Ferris |title= Encyclopedia of Southern Culture |isbn=0807818232 |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |year= 1989 |via= [[Documenting the American South]] |chapterurl=http://docsouth.unc.edu/southlit/intro.html |chapter=Beginnings of Southern Literature }}</ref>

Literary figures of the antebellum period included [[Edgar Allan Poe]] and Virginia-born writers [[William Alexander Caruthers]] (1802–1846), [[John Esten Cooke]] (1830-1886), [[Philip Pendleton Cooke]] (1816 -1850), [[Nathaniel Beverley Tucker]] (1784-1851).<ref>{{cite book |editor1= Charles Reagan Wilson |editor2= William Ferris |title= Encyclopedia of Southern Culture |isbn=0807818232 |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |year= 1989 |via=Documenting the American South |chapterurl=http://docsouth.unc.edu/southlit/antebellum.html |chapter=Antebellum Era }}</ref> The ''[[Southern Literary Messenger]]'' launched in Richmond in 1834.{{sfn|Hayes|2015}}

Marion Fontaine Cabell Tyree's ''Housekeeping in Old Virginia,'' a [[cookbook]], was published in Richmond in 1878.<ref>{{citation |url=http://digital.lib.msu.edu/projects/cookbooks/html/browse_int/browse_interest_regional.html#s |title= Regional American Cooking: South and Border States |work=Feeding America: the Historic American Cookbook Project |publisher=Michigan State University |accessdate= March 13, 2017 }}</ref>

==Organizations==
The Poetry Society of Virginia formed in 1923.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://poetrysocietyofvirginia.org/about-psv/ |title=About PSV |publisher= Poetry Society of Virginia |accessdate= March 11, 2017 }}</ref>

==Awards and events==
The [[Virginia General Assembly]] created the position of [[Poet Laureate of Virginia]] in 1936.

